00:00:28.226 --> 00:00:34.674
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:34.674 --> 00:00:36.650
BRIAN OLSON: So
if you've ever had

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:40.380
the feeling that our democracy
is not entirely fair,

00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:43.090
and sometimes the deck
is stacked, you're right.

00:00:43.090 --> 00:00:47.630
In a lot of places,
we have democracy

00:00:47.630 --> 00:00:50.690
that has been distorted
by the state legislature,

00:00:50.690 --> 00:00:54.110
using their power to make sure
that their favorite candidate

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:55.460
wins.

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:59.890
In Florida in 2010, they
passed by ballot initiative

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:04.640
a new law to prevent that from
happening, but it didn't work.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:07.880
This map that the Florida State
legislature drew was later

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:09.605
thrown out by court decision.

00:01:12.380 --> 00:01:14.690
So that's what we
call gerrymandering.

00:01:14.690 --> 00:01:17.750
Gerrymandering is the
distortion of districts,

00:01:17.750 --> 00:01:21.350
representational districts,
toward some political end.

00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:23.160
How does it work?

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:26.840
So let's say you've got
this hypothetical map that

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:30.080
has the 60-40 split in
its population favoring

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:31.760
the green people.

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:33.680
Now, if you cut that up
in a very simple way,

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:36.156
you get three districts
that the green people win,

00:01:36.156 --> 00:01:38.030
and two districts that
the purple people win,

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:40.580
preserving that ratio.

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:43.760
If you cut it differently, and
you pack enough green people

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:45.500
into just a couple
of districts, you

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:48.920
can get three districts where
the purple minority wins,

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:51.560
thus inverting and
letting the minority power

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:56.270
have the majority power in that
five-person state legislature.

00:01:56.270 --> 00:01:59.690
Or if you do it the other way,
and you split the purple people

00:01:59.690 --> 00:02:02.240
just right, they don't
get a majority anywhere,

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:03.830
and they're completely shut out.

00:02:03.830 --> 00:02:05.750
These strategies of
"packing and cracking"

00:02:05.750 --> 00:02:09.289
have been used in many
places around our country.

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:11.990
In Florida, this
district was found

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:15.080
to be illegally
packing too many people

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:17.930
of an under-represented
group into one district

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:22.060
so that they would have
less influence elsewhere.

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:24.820
Florida was doing that in 2012.

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:28.330
But this is gerrymandering from
1812 here in Massachusetts,

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:30.190
where the term was invented.

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:32.890
Governor Elbridge
Gerry signed into law

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:35.380
this map that was drawn
into political cartoon

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:38.410
as this monstrous
dragon, a salamander--

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:40.990
thus coining the "gerrymander."

00:02:40.990 --> 00:02:45.040
It's gotten a lot worse lately,
because computers have allowed

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:48.220
people to draw lines
very finely, looking

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:50.860
at all the demographics
down to little pockets

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:52.840
of hundred people
here and there,

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:55.720
and thus making
designer districts just

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:57.130
for their particular purpose.

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:03.130
But what if we used that
same computational power

00:03:03.130 --> 00:03:06.490
to make completely
impartial districts that

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:09.910
just tried to make
local representation

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:12.100
without any political bias?

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:14.638
You might get
something like this.

00:03:14.638 --> 00:03:17.800
This is a map that I made
with my open source software.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:19.720
We started to be able
to make this kind of map

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:22.300
about 10 years ago,
when home computers got

00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:24.880
fast enough to do this.

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:29.620
So following the 2010 census,
I downloaded all of the data,

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:31.750
ran my home computer
for six months,

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:34.750
and generated 137 maps for
all the states and state

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:37.030
legislatures, except
for a few where there

00:03:37.030 --> 00:03:38.470
were bugs I'm still working on.

00:03:38.470 --> 00:03:40.390
This is North Carolina.

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:46.630
North Carolina has been in a
constitutional crisis for years

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:49.330
now over their gerrymandering.

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:52.990
They have had three years in a
row there are maps thrown out

00:03:52.990 --> 00:03:55.510
by court, and they had
to go back and fix them I

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:57.250
forget which generation
of the map it is.

00:03:57.250 --> 00:04:00.190
This is probably
the map from 2013.

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:01.630
You can see this
big red district

00:04:01.630 --> 00:04:05.050
reaching into and around three
other districts around it.

00:04:05.050 --> 00:04:06.880
This pink district
pinches down as

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:08.800
narrow as possible
while reaching out

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.780
to grab other areas.

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:11.835
This is nuts.

00:04:11.835 --> 00:04:13.210
And the court has
found that this

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:19.390
is nuts and illegal and
trying to distort the system.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:22.930
It could be like this, though.

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:25.900
You can go from the
hallmarks of gerrymandering,

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:27.340
all of these fiddly
bits reaching

00:04:27.340 --> 00:04:31.600
into and around everything,
to soap bubbles.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:36.940
Maryland also has one of the
most distorted, contorted

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:39.800
district mappings
I've ever seen.

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:42.280
This is a Democratic
Party gerrymander

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.670
based on the Maryland
State legislature's

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:47.150
Democratic majority.

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:49.570
The previous two were
Republican gerrymanders.

00:04:49.570 --> 00:04:52.510
Maryland's Republican
governor made some news

00:04:52.510 --> 00:04:55.660
briefly calling out
for help, can somebody

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:57.400
please help fix my state?

00:04:57.400 --> 00:04:59.350
To which President
Obama said, yeah,

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:04.540
we should fix gerrymandering
everywhere, please.

00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:05.620
It could be like this.

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:13.930
So my point about
gerrymandering is that there

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:15.850
is technology possible.

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:17.800
There is political
will on both sides

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:22.250
of the aisle in various places
to want to make a saner system.

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:24.040
So let's do it.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.260
So how did I do it?

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:29.380
I wrote effectively
a custom GIS stack--

00:05:29.380 --> 00:05:31.960
Geographic Information Systems.

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:34.600
It was a lot of code
and various tools,

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.680
depending on what part
I was going to do.

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:39.820
But it's pretty efficient.

00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:41.200
It runs on home computers.

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:42.110
It's open source.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:44.651
You can all go look at it, but
you probably wouldn't want to.

00:05:44.651 --> 00:05:48.770
It's not very pretty code,
but I'm working on that.

00:05:48.770 --> 00:05:52.400
And I'm going to update it
again for the 2020 cycle.

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:56.320
It does that kind of
data pre-processing stuff

00:05:56.320 --> 00:05:59.200
you'd expect, because it
downloads raw census data,

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:03.940
turns it into just the data
needed to do redistricting,

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:05.080
solves that.

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:07.810
It can run in a distributed
fashion on as many computers

00:06:07.810 --> 00:06:09.130
as you throw at it.

00:06:09.130 --> 00:06:13.360
And then finally
rendering the map output.

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:16.150
What data do you actually
need to run this?

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.420
The census data provides
blocks as the lowest

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.550
level of information they have.

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:24.460
Sometimes literally
a city block,

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:28.900
sometimes just miles and
miles and acres and acres

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:32.230
of land in Montana between
this stream and that stream.

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:34.660
But blocks that are
blatantly split up

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:37.096
based on some political
or physical boundary.

00:06:37.096 --> 00:06:38.470
And the whole
country is split up

00:06:38.470 --> 00:06:41.890
into about 9 and 1/2
million blocks of data.

00:06:41.890 --> 00:06:44.890
Some blocks have just 100
people or zero people.

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:47.860
Some blocks have 1,000 people.

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:49.960
Each of those blocks
has a position.

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:52.000
It has its neighbors,
because districts

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.100
have to be contiguous.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:55.960
They can't have part
of a district here

00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:58.510
and part of a district here
with nothing in between.

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:00.580
Although sometimes a
gerrymandered district

00:07:00.580 --> 00:07:03.520
will have a town over
here, a town over here,

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:05.555
and a thin strip
of road in between.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:12.400
Land area and information.

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:17.090
So my process takes the
raw census data down from 2

00:07:17.090 --> 00:07:20.640
and 1/2 gigabytes of raw data
down to about 16 megabytes

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:22.620
for a typical state
of what I actually

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:23.940
need to solve this problem.

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:26.440
Makes it much more tractable.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:30.690
So what I'm actually solving for
in my definition of compactness

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:32.430
is the average
distance per person

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.260
to the center of their district.

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:37.080
If this little
map is a district,

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:40.290
and those are blocks with
population counts in them,

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.240
I find the center
of the district

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:44.550
and then measure the distance
to all of those blocks

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:46.650
and weight it by the population.

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:50.640
And minimizing for that score
is how I identify a locality.

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:54.990
A locality will be a relatively
high-density population area

00:07:54.990 --> 00:07:57.750
surrounded by a more
sparse area around it

00:07:57.750 --> 00:08:01.020
in a typical town,
city arrangement.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:03.600
And that's all I'm
optimizing for.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:09.480
Just compact localities, and
no political or demographic

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:11.280
information.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:14.040
You can look at the demographic
information, though.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:17.620
The census provides
lots of race-

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:20.250
and income-based demographics.

00:08:20.250 --> 00:08:24.180
And one of the big questions
is, the Voting Rights

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:26.340
Act used to specify
that there would

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:29.220
be a certain kind of
gerrymandering for good.

00:08:29.220 --> 00:08:31.860
There shall be,
in certain states,

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:34.980
a majority minority
district to make sure

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:40.140
you get a black congressman
from Georgia, for example.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:45.870
And my system does not try to
make those, but in a few states

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:49.470
it winds up with them
anyway, just because of where

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:53.130
people are self-sorting into
where they choose to live.

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:59.730
So that's still an open question
about how we do this, though.

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:04.110
The details are a heuristic
hill-climbing search.

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:08.010
I can talk to you more about
that if you're really curious.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:12.160
This is one run through the data
of getting a little bit better,

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:15.360
a little bit better, as
it's searching for a better

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:16.690
solution.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:19.350
So that's the short, short
version of gerrymandering

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:24.150
and what you can do to
make an impartial map.

00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:27.750
There's one other big fix that
I'd like to see in our system,

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:31.170
and that is when we actually
go to vote for people,

00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:33.540
we can do better.

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:37.350
You should never, ever
again, if at all possible,

00:09:37.350 --> 00:09:39.960
pick just one
person on a ballot.

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:43.050
You all know the problem
of being told, oh,

00:09:43.050 --> 00:09:46.170
don't vote for them, you're
throwing your vote away.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:47.290
It's a two-party system.

00:09:47.290 --> 00:09:49.800
You have to vote for one of us.

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:52.530
But we can do better.

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:54.150
Once upon a time,
a mathematician

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:57.330
proved that if you only
have one choice, that's

00:09:57.330 --> 00:10:00.580
only enough information to
pick between two choices.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:03.900
If you only get to mark
one person on your ballot,

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:07.000
it will devolve to
a two-party system.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.800
So let's do better.

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:11.670
Let's rank our choices, first,
second, third, and so on,

00:10:11.670 --> 00:10:15.990
or rate them on some scale,
like a five-star scale,

00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:19.650
or A through F letter
grading, or minus 10 to 10.

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:23.490
Or even just approve,
disapprove on each candidate

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:28.140
gives you better results
than picking one.

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:29.730
But this is just data.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:32.640
If you can say something
about every candidate,

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:34.470
you're not throwing
your vote away.

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:36.870
You have said something
about every candidate.

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.210
You said, yes, I like
this one, and this one's

00:10:39.210 --> 00:10:41.532
OK, and that one--
no, no, not them.

00:10:41.532 --> 00:10:42.990
And if you don't
get your favorite,

00:10:42.990 --> 00:10:45.030
you might get your
second favorite.

00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:49.740
So you can vote for the weird,
obscure, idealistic candidate

00:10:49.740 --> 00:10:52.410
who just really gets
you moving, and then you

00:10:52.410 --> 00:10:54.640
can have your second choice,
yeah, popular, mediocre,

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:55.770
or whatever.

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:58.800
And then, if it's
just not your year,

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:00.540
and you don't get
any of them, you

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:03.150
can keep ranking
your vote on down,

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:07.470
and maybe you can help the other
party elect a moderate instead

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:09.280
of their crazy person.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.480
So ranked choice voting is good.

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:16.020
But there are many algorithms
to count these ballots,

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:19.170
and they all have trade-offs.

00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:21.750
There was a famous
theorem that proved

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:26.490
you can't have a perfect system
based on some set of qualities

00:11:26.490 --> 00:11:28.740
that all sound good,
and it was proven

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:31.650
you can't have all of those
qualities at the same time.

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:33.525
But you can still have
a pretty good system.

00:11:33.525 --> 00:11:35.400
You can still have a
better system, and maybe

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:36.600
a best system.

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:39.870
And our current system
is the worst system

00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:41.720
aside from actual tyranny.

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:42.720
So here's one algorithm.

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:44.100
Instant runoff voting.

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:45.780
So you have a rankings ballot.

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:48.630
You count up all the
first choice votes.

00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:52.680
If someone has a simple
majority, great, they win.

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:56.160
Otherwise, whoever has the
fewest first choice votes,

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:57.750
you disqualify them.

00:11:57.750 --> 00:12:01.350
And all of those ballots, well,
let's count their second choice

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:02.610
vote now.

00:12:02.610 --> 00:12:07.160
And this repeats, disqualifying
until finally somebody wins.

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:08.350
Very simple system.

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:10.300
It was used in
Burlington, Vermont,

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:13.150
for a couple mayoral elections.

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:18.190
And after you filter out
the lesser candidates,

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:23.440
here are just the dramatic
finish of that election, where

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:26.680
people are getting
disqualified one by one,

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:28.702
and then finally
you have a winner.

00:12:28.702 --> 00:12:30.160
One thing you can
see about this is

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:34.420
the vote counts for the
eventual winners keep going up.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:38.650
As Dan Smith's candidate's
votes are disqualified,

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:42.260
well, they had a second choice
of one of the other candidates.

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:44.320
So those counts go up.

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:46.600
As Andy Montroll
is disqualified,

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:49.780
the other counts go up as
those votes are transferred.

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:51.040
Another algorithm.

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:53.090
Condorcet method,
or Con-dor-say.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:56.260
A French mathematician
from 100 years ago.

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:58.690
I like to think of this
as a virtual round robin

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:02.320
tournament, where the match
score between each candidate

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.780
is how many people
like A higher than B

00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:07.390
versus how many people
like B higher than A.

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:09.190
And that's the score
of them, and if more

00:13:09.190 --> 00:13:12.760
people like A higher than
B than like B more than A,

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:13.720
then A should win.

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:18.610
A has defeated B. A ranked vote
says, I like A higher than B,

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:20.770
and A higher than C,
and A higher than D,

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:22.570
and I also like B higher than C.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:24.280
So you have
information about all

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:27.970
of these hypothetical pairings,
and you can count it up,

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:31.300
and the result looks
something like this.

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:35.360
This count says that
from the same Burlington,

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:36.940
Vermont election data--

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:39.430
they published the
full anonymized vote

00:13:39.430 --> 00:13:44.780
set, which is really useful
for research like this.

00:13:44.780 --> 00:13:49.090
This count says that 4,067
people liked Andy Montroll

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:53.830
better than Bob Kiss,
and 3,477 people

00:13:53.830 --> 00:13:56.680
liked Bob Kiss better
than Andy Montroll.

00:13:56.680 --> 00:14:01.120
And 4,500 people liked
Andy more than Kurt or Dan.

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:02.000
b is different.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.690
This is a different outcome
than the instant runoff voting

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:05.830
election.

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:09.190
This is saying more
people like Andy Montroll

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:11.260
than Bob Kiss or Kurt Wright.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:15.970
But the previous election was
that Bob Kiss wound up winning.

00:14:15.970 --> 00:14:17.710
How did this happen?

00:14:17.710 --> 00:14:23.680
Andy Montroll had a huge support
at the second choice level.

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:29.290
Kurt Wright and Bob Kiss had
really fanatic fans, but not

00:14:29.290 --> 00:14:31.780
so many of them in the end.

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:37.330
So Andy Montroll might have
been the centrist candidate that

00:14:37.330 --> 00:14:40.190
made a lot of
people pretty happy,

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:44.320
but he wasn't the first choice,
and instant runoff voting only

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:49.600
looks at the first choice,
whereas a virtual round robin

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:52.820
election looks at all
of the data at once.

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:58.270
So just from a perspective of
navigating the solution space,

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:01.060
Condorcet is a better algorithm.

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:04.510
And it requires exactly
the same inputs.

00:15:04.510 --> 00:15:07.480
A rankings ballot, first,
second, third, and so on.

00:15:07.480 --> 00:15:09.850
Instant runoff voting was
used in Burlington, Vermont

00:15:09.850 --> 00:15:13.750
twice and then repealed,
because they wound up really

00:15:13.750 --> 00:15:17.980
not liking the guy it
elected on the second try.

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:21.040
And they could have had
a different outcome.

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:23.020
The algorithm matters.

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:26.770
In this age of search
engines and news feeds,

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.000
the algorithm matters.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.920
You have a big pile
of data, but then

00:15:29.920 --> 00:15:31.640
what do you actually do with it?

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:35.980
And one more thing out
there is that if you're

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:38.260
picking more than
one person, there's

00:15:38.260 --> 00:15:40.840
an even more powerful
thing you can do.

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:43.780
Proportional representation
is the notion

00:15:43.780 --> 00:15:48.910
that if you're electing a city
council or a state legislature,

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:52.510
if 20% of the people show up
in some constituency and vote

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:55.900
for whatever their
favorite cause is, then

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:59.410
20% of the seats
of the legislature

00:15:59.410 --> 00:16:02.140
should go to that
20% group of people.

00:16:02.140 --> 00:16:04.390
That's proportional
representation.

00:16:04.390 --> 00:16:08.590
And there's an algorithm called
single transferable vote, which

00:16:08.590 --> 00:16:12.070
is used to achieve just
that in the Cambridge City

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:16.840
Council and a few
parliaments around the world,

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:17.920
like the Irish Senate.

00:16:17.920 --> 00:16:21.060
And they're trying
it out in Australia.

00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:25.180
And I think this is a really
powerful hack on democracy,

00:16:25.180 --> 00:16:31.370
because what if you had a state
legislature that was not--

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:35.680
if it was 40 people, and it
wasn't 21 Democrats and 19

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:40.510
Republicans, it was 13
Democrats, 12 Republicans,

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:44.310
five Greens, three Libertarians,
and, I don't know, that guy.

00:16:47.050 --> 00:16:49.840
That would be a much
more interesting

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:53.080
and vibrant and
representative democracy.

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:55.180
This is about representing us.

00:16:55.180 --> 00:16:58.240
All of this is about
representing us,

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:00.970
whether we are people
who live in an area

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:04.810
and might have common concerns,
like, you live near Boston.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:06.490
You probably want the T to run.

00:17:06.490 --> 00:17:08.230
Or you live near Amherst.

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:12.040
You want-- well, I don't know
what they want in Amherst.

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:14.990
And that's part of the problem.

00:17:14.990 --> 00:17:18.010
Or you can have the
ideological representation

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:21.910
of a proportional representation
system, where you get together

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:26.470
and say, we all really care
about preserving our parks

00:17:26.470 --> 00:17:28.870
and open spaces
and green spaces.

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:31.420
And if 10% of the people
show up and vote for that,

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:34.090
then they are going to get a
couple of seats that are just

00:17:34.090 --> 00:17:35.890
really going to push
for that and introduce

00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:39.410
new legislation around that and
build coalitions around that.

00:17:39.410 --> 00:17:44.440
So these are what I think
are the most important hacks

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:46.690
that we can do to
improve our continuing

00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:48.700
democratic experiment.

00:17:48.700 --> 00:17:49.483
Thank you.

00:17:49.483 --> 00:17:56.878
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:56.878 --> 00:17:57.864
Questions?

00:18:01.674 --> 00:18:03.840
AUDIENCE: I was just curious
what your thoughts were

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:06.840
on approval voting, where
you choose which candidates

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:08.640
you like and which
you don't like,

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:11.354
and then whoever gets
the most acceptance wins.

00:18:11.354 --> 00:18:13.770
Which is a little simplier
than some of the other systems,

00:18:13.770 --> 00:18:15.120
but still usually gets
pretty good results,

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:16.045
from what I've seen.

00:18:16.045 --> 00:18:17.100
BRIAN OLSON: Yes.

00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:18.450
It is definitely simpler.

00:18:18.450 --> 00:18:21.322
It definitely gives
pretty good results.

00:18:21.322 --> 00:18:23.280
Another thing I've done
that I didn't show here

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:28.240
is run simulations on
millions of simulated voters.

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:29.430
It's a model.

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:30.720
It's maybe not the best model.

00:18:30.720 --> 00:18:33.600
But it shows that, yes,
approval is pretty good.

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:36.610
I just find it
unsatisfying personally.

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:40.470
I want to say, I like this
guy better than this guy.

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:44.250
And so I would prefer a
rankings or a ratings ballot.

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:46.560
But yes, approval
is pretty good.

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:50.700
And if it's the matter of, if
you're just designing a survey

00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:53.820
form, if you can just
switch from radio buttons

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:57.000
to checkboxes, that's all you
need to do to get better data.

00:18:59.952 --> 00:19:00.880
AUDIENCE: Hi, Brian.

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:02.007
Thank you.

00:19:02.007 --> 00:19:03.590
First of all, I
wanted to say that I'm

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:06.050
on the board of an organization
called Voter Choice

00:19:06.050 --> 00:19:08.360
Massachusetts, where we're
advancing ranked choice

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:09.770
voting here in Massachusetts.

00:19:09.770 --> 00:19:13.740
And I have a sign-up sheet,
if anybody wants to sign up.

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:18.356
We have legislation
and other things.

00:19:18.356 --> 00:19:19.730
I do want to
respond a little bit

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:23.960
to the criticism of the
instant runoff algorithm.

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:26.202
You bring up Burlington,
and Burlington's not

00:19:26.202 --> 00:19:27.410
the only city that's used it.

00:19:27.410 --> 00:19:29.270
Currently, 11 cities
in the United States

00:19:29.270 --> 00:19:32.240
use that form of
ranked choice voting.

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:35.030
And there's been over
150 elections since 2004

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:36.830
using that version.

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:40.970
The Burlington 2009
election is the only one

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:45.470
where the instant runoff result
has differed from the Condorcet

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:48.440
result. So in practice,
it seems to be

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:50.075
a very, very rare outcome.

00:19:50.075 --> 00:19:53.150
So that's one comment
I wanted to make.

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:55.400
And the other thing is that
I'm a little bit concerned

00:19:55.400 --> 00:19:57.050
with the Condorcet
algorithm about some

00:19:57.050 --> 00:20:01.130
of the strategic manipulations
that it is vulnerable to.

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:03.200
For example, two front-runners.

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:08.690
If you insincerely rank your
formidable opponent last,

00:20:08.690 --> 00:20:10.400
that can benefit you.

00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:12.230
Or bullet voting
your first choice

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:14.960
and not deciding to rank
the rest of the choices

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:17.420
can benefit that first
choice, can benefit

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:19.160
that favorite candidate.

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:22.490
And those are certain
strategic vulnerabilities

00:20:22.490 --> 00:20:25.541
that the instant runoff
version is immune to,

00:20:25.541 --> 00:20:27.290
and I think that's
part of the reason it's

00:20:27.290 --> 00:20:31.610
been successful in being
implemented across the country.

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:35.600
And most recently, Maine became
the first state in the nation

00:20:35.600 --> 00:20:36.800
to enact it--

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:40.660
historic first state nation to
enact it for statewide offices.

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:43.060
So that's my commentary on this.

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:45.260
BRIAN OLSON: I look forward
to the Maine experiment.

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:46.760
I wish them well.

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:48.770
I hope they release
full data so that we

00:20:48.770 --> 00:20:51.550
can analyze it properly.

00:20:51.550 --> 00:20:55.580
And yes, it's true that most
of the time instant runoff

00:20:55.580 --> 00:20:58.430
voting and Condorcet agree.

00:20:58.430 --> 00:21:00.710
My argument is that
for no additional cost,

00:21:00.710 --> 00:21:04.250
you can get a better choice
when they don't agree.

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:05.630
The strategic concerns?

00:21:08.490 --> 00:21:12.740
There's what is sometimes called
the favorite betrayal problem

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:17.690
of, you have your favorite, and
so you really want them to win,

00:21:17.690 --> 00:21:19.400
so you vote for them first.

00:21:19.400 --> 00:21:23.090
And then you vote for
your second favorite,

00:21:23.090 --> 00:21:27.500
but if it hadn't been for that
vote for that second favorite,

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:29.630
your favorite would have won.

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:32.960
And instant runoff
voting doesn't do that,

00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:35.900
because it doesn't look
at your second favorite.

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:42.830
But I think that's a flawed
analysis, because it's not just

00:21:42.830 --> 00:21:43.650
all about you.

00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:46.910
It's also about what
can we all agree on.

00:21:46.910 --> 00:21:51.610
Your second choice is
also pretty good, I hope.

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:55.280
And so if you say, well,
this is pretty good,

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:57.950
and it makes the rest
of the group also happy,

00:21:57.950 --> 00:21:59.195
that should be an OK outcome.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:06.260
And if you are voting
dishonestly and saying,

00:22:06.260 --> 00:22:11.960
yes, I want Hillary
first and Bernie last,

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:13.760
then you are shooting
yourself in the foot.

00:22:13.760 --> 00:22:14.420
Don't do that.

00:22:14.420 --> 00:22:15.440
Please don't do that.

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:18.860
Please just vote honestly
and say I like Hillary first

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:21.310
and Bernie second, or I like
Bernie first and Hillary

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:26.510
second, or I like Winona
LaDuke first and whatever else,

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:28.520
and then Hillary
and then Bernie.

00:22:28.520 --> 00:22:34.040
Just vote honestly, and if
we implement a good system,

00:22:34.040 --> 00:22:37.040
it will do the right thing
with that honest vote.

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:41.172
So that's what I would
say, is vote honestly.

00:22:41.172 --> 00:22:42.630
If you don't get
your first choice,

00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:44.004
you might get your
second choice,

00:22:44.004 --> 00:22:47.455
and that should
still be pretty good.

00:22:47.455 --> 00:22:51.160
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about policy.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:53.650
I forgot about Maine, and I'm
really excited that Maine is

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:56.350
moving to ranked choice voting.

00:22:56.350 --> 00:22:59.380
But in general, with both
gerrymandering and things

00:22:59.380 --> 00:23:02.920
like ranked choice
voting, I notice

00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:05.320
that generally the
people in charge

00:23:05.320 --> 00:23:08.680
of making the change
to better systems

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:11.290
are the people in
power, who probably

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:13.540
stand to benefit the least.

00:23:13.540 --> 00:23:15.940
If you want to keep control
of the two-party system

00:23:15.940 --> 00:23:17.470
because it works
fairly well for you

00:23:17.470 --> 00:23:20.350
and it works fairly well for
Democrats and Republicans,

00:23:20.350 --> 00:23:22.900
you probably aren't
excited to hear

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:25.330
about these exciting
new plans to help

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:28.240
get third-party candidates or
vote for multiple candidates,

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:31.690
rather than being forced to pick
between the two major parties.

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:34.570
So I was wondering if
you could speak to--

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:36.730
in spite of that,
what I perceive

00:23:36.730 --> 00:23:39.370
as an obstacle,
what people can do

00:23:39.370 --> 00:23:43.810
to keep this conversation going
and keep progress growing.

00:23:43.810 --> 00:23:44.800
BRIAN OLSON: Right.

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:49.390
Getting it through the
traditional legislative process

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:50.250
is--

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:52.000
there is an obvious
conflict of interest

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:55.930
between people who won via
the old system versus enacting

00:23:55.930 --> 00:23:57.880
a new system.

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:01.630
And so I believe that most
of the time it gets in,

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:03.670
it gets in via
ballot initiative.

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:05.239
Direct democracy.

00:24:05.239 --> 00:24:07.280
People put something on
the ballot, they vote it,

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:08.830
it becomes law.

00:24:08.830 --> 00:24:12.610
That's what happened in Maine
and several other places.

00:24:12.610 --> 00:24:14.710
Even in the Burlington
City Council.

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:16.780
The Burlington
mayoral election was

00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:19.060
something that was
voted on, a proposition

00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:21.730
that was locally voted on
directly by the people,

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:23.200
in and out.

00:24:25.960 --> 00:24:29.080
AUDIENCE: This is kind of a
similar comment or question,

00:24:29.080 --> 00:24:32.410
but with gerrymandering
in particular,

00:24:32.410 --> 00:24:35.380
I think as you
mentioned, there's

00:24:35.380 --> 00:24:40.750
a lot of incentive for
people to keep doing it.

00:24:40.750 --> 00:24:45.430
And I can see relinquishing
all the control to a computer

00:24:45.430 --> 00:24:47.920
might be hard, or an algorithm.

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:50.500
What are your
thoughts on proposals

00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:54.550
of just limiting
the amount of damage

00:24:54.550 --> 00:24:56.080
that gerrymandering can do?

00:24:56.080 --> 00:24:58.480
One thing that I've
seen or suggested

00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:00.670
is, you've got n
districts, you can

00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:03.820
draw n minus 1 straight
line segments on the map,

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:06.504
or some other--

00:25:06.504 --> 00:25:08.170
because right now,
like you say, there's

00:25:08.170 --> 00:25:12.160
just contiguousness of a space.

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:15.880
But you could have some
aspect ratio or something

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:18.910
like that that constrains
the problem such

00:25:18.910 --> 00:25:22.330
that there is
still some control,

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:26.740
but hopefully not as ridiculous
as some of these maps

00:25:26.740 --> 00:25:27.340
you've shown.

00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:30.440
BRIAN OLSON: Yeah, that's
a really good question.

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:33.760
One of the ways that this
is going through my work

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:38.020
and through others is
computational accountability

00:25:38.020 --> 00:25:39.640
of gerrymandering.

00:25:39.640 --> 00:25:41.230
There was recent
work out of Illinois

00:25:41.230 --> 00:25:44.800
where they just simulated
hundreds of thousands

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:48.040
of plausible maps and then
analyzed the current map

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:50.950
and saying, is this
outcome likely,

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:53.980
or is this outcome
unlikely, and therefore

00:25:53.980 --> 00:25:56.779
evidence of malfeasance.

00:25:56.779 --> 00:25:58.195
So that's an
interesting approach.

00:26:01.330 --> 00:26:04.370
So in passing laws
one state at a time,

00:26:04.370 --> 00:26:07.060
there's a unilateral
disarmament problem,

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:10.390
where if a blue state
gives up its gerrymander,

00:26:10.390 --> 00:26:13.330
and a red state keeps
its gerrymander, then

00:26:13.330 --> 00:26:15.910
the Congress is distorted.

00:26:15.910 --> 00:26:20.170
So we need something that
can be applied everywhere.

00:26:20.170 --> 00:26:25.210
And in that strategic
vein, I know one person

00:26:25.210 --> 00:26:29.500
who's advocating computational
accountability and court

00:26:29.500 --> 00:26:34.030
challenges, because
the ACLU and the League

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:36.220
of Women Voters and
Common Cause can

00:26:36.220 --> 00:26:39.010
go into a state that
has gerrymandered

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:43.180
and sue them to get
it un-gerrymandered.

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:45.910
And you can apply a
national lawyering dollars

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:48.240
to fix a local problem.

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:50.725
And there's a certain
logic to that strategy.

00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:05.040
Also, giving up the pen entirely
and letting a computer do it

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:08.100
fully automatically,
obviously we'll

00:27:08.100 --> 00:27:13.830
have missed some opportunities
that a good person looking

00:27:13.830 --> 00:27:15.600
at a map would do.

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:18.840
Someone who really
understands Massachusetts

00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:22.290
could draw lines to say, oh,
these people go together,

00:27:22.290 --> 00:27:24.330
because reasons.

