00:37:34.569 --> 00:37:35.110
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:38.740
A question about your
redistricting algorithm.

00:37:42.310 --> 00:37:45.340
Why did you choose average
distance to the center

00:37:45.340 --> 00:37:48.211
as the thing to maximize for?

00:37:48.211 --> 00:37:49.210
Are there other options?

00:37:49.210 --> 00:37:50.950
What other types of
things did you look at?

00:37:50.950 --> 00:37:51.700
BRIAN OLSON: Sure.

00:37:51.700 --> 00:37:56.560
There are dozens of proposed
measures of what is generally

00:37:56.560 --> 00:37:59.450
called compactness.

00:37:59.450 --> 00:38:03.000
The opposite of compactness
is the sprawling tendrils

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.620
of tentacled monster districts.

00:38:05.620 --> 00:38:07.960
So there are lots
of ways of measuring

00:38:07.960 --> 00:38:09.550
what a compact district is.

00:38:09.550 --> 00:38:12.280
A lot of them are
purely geometrical.

00:38:12.280 --> 00:38:14.620
The length of the perimeter
around the district.

00:38:14.620 --> 00:38:18.490
The ratio of the area of
the district to the area

00:38:18.490 --> 00:38:22.420
of the smallest enclosing
circle of the district.

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:24.860
And these kinds of things.

00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:28.450
But what these purely
geometrical measures don't do

00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:31.300
is, they don't tell you
anything about the distribution

00:38:31.300 --> 00:38:33.580
of the people
inside the district.

00:38:33.580 --> 00:38:36.640
So imagine, if you will, a
perfectly circular district.

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:38.410
This is perfectly compact.

00:38:38.410 --> 00:38:40.860
What if it is
perfectly circular,

00:38:40.860 --> 00:38:44.640
but there is a huge
city off on one edge,

00:38:44.640 --> 00:38:46.720
and then rural
areas out from it?

00:38:46.720 --> 00:38:50.800
That is perhaps not the ideal
of having a perfectly circular

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:53.620
district that is just
a bull's eye on a city,

00:38:53.620 --> 00:38:56.900
that it's representing
that city and metro area.

00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:58.390
So that's what I
wanted to do, is

00:38:58.390 --> 00:39:01.570
by measuring the
distribution of the people,

00:39:01.570 --> 00:39:05.560
how far away are the people from
the center of their district?

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:09.492
How tightly packed
are the people?

00:39:09.492 --> 00:39:11.200
So that's what I really
wanted to measure

00:39:11.200 --> 00:39:14.740
in designing my measure.

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:17.470
There are still some variations.

00:39:17.470 --> 00:39:19.460
I'm still looking
into other things.

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:23.230
One thing I'm doing is
I'm measuring the land

00:39:23.230 --> 00:39:26.860
area of the district and finding
the center of the land area,

00:39:26.860 --> 00:39:28.780
and measuring the
distance to people.

00:39:28.780 --> 00:39:31.960
Maybe I should just completely
forget about land entirely

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:34.660
and measure the population
center of the district,

00:39:34.660 --> 00:39:38.200
and measure the distance
from people to people.

00:39:38.200 --> 00:39:41.950
And on even-numbered
days, I believe in one,

00:39:41.950 --> 00:39:43.280
and odd numbers the other.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:46.456
But I implemented this one,
and I think it's pretty good.

00:39:46.456 --> 00:39:49.554
