I mean, that is
especially true in

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:48.610
the current political climate.

00:41:48.610 --> 00:41:51.430
There are times when
having a local rep

00:41:51.430 --> 00:41:53.140
is still awfully
handy, and people

00:41:53.140 --> 00:41:56.320
will identify with a local
representative, which

00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:59.400
is why in a bicameral system,
I would have one of each.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:02.410
I would have a districted
local representative

00:42:02.410 --> 00:42:07.150
and the at-large proportional
ideological representative.

00:42:07.150 --> 00:42:11.650
And there's a current
court case in Wisconsin

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:16.690
that I think is sitting
with SCOTUS right now that

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:21.100
is putting this to the
test of, will Wisconsin

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:25.090
be required to gerrymander
for both parties?

00:42:25.090 --> 00:42:29.110
Will it be required to achieve
proportional representation

00:42:29.110 --> 00:42:34.570
by district, saying, OK,
this state is 60% Republican

00:42:34.570 --> 00:42:36.160
and 40% Democrat.

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:38.980
We should make sure that our
state legislature and our US

00:42:38.980 --> 00:42:41.560
House seats break
in the same way,

00:42:41.560 --> 00:42:45.070
even if that means that 49%
of people in every district

00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:46.870
are unhappy?

00:42:46.870 --> 00:42:49.390
Whereas if you had a
proportional system,

00:42:49.390 --> 00:42:52.210
you're not in a district,
and you might still

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:57.730
have some representative
that you feel affinity for?

00:42:57.730 --> 00:43:02.380
So yeah, I see people trying
to achieve proportionality

00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:04.630
through districting,
and I find that to be

00:43:04.630 --> 00:43:06.190
a terribly awkward fit.

00:43:06.190 --> 00:43:07.690
And I think what
they actually want

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:11.290
is a more direct proportional
system, if we could just

00:43:11.290 --> 00:43:14.050
figure out a way to
broach the subject

00:43:14.050 --> 00:43:18.015
and start down that reform path.

00:43:18.015 --> 00:43:20.140
AUDIENCE: The second question
I had is a little bit

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:21.800
orthogonal to the talk.

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:26.770
But it used to be that
the Senate and the US

00:43:26.770 --> 00:43:30.400
elected representatives were
elected by state legislatures,

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:33.607
rather than directly
from the people.

00:43:33.607 --> 00:43:35.440
And this, I think, was
viewed as a mechanism

00:43:35.440 --> 00:43:42.245
to squash short-term passions.

00:43:44.930 --> 00:43:48.770
My question is, what do you
think about these tiered voting

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:50.726
systems?

00:43:50.726 --> 00:43:53.810
BRIAN OLSON: There is
definitely a rationale

00:43:53.810 --> 00:43:58.250
for a hierarchical system,
where each layer elects

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:00.770
the layer above it.

00:44:00.770 --> 00:44:02.570
You get network effects.

00:44:02.570 --> 00:44:05.630
Every layer has its own--

00:44:05.630 --> 00:44:06.620
what's that guy?

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:14.900
The number, 150-- so if there's
only so many relationships

00:44:14.900 --> 00:44:18.080
that you can carry
on as a human, then

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:24.700
every layer mimics
that star topology.

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:27.920
And I think that can make sense.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:29.945
Direct democracy has its place.

00:44:32.510 --> 00:44:34.340
So let's take the president.

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:37.790
Right now, we have a
fake direct election

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:41.180
And every four years,
this frustrates me,

00:44:41.180 --> 00:44:44.240
and I wish we had either
a real direct election

00:44:44.240 --> 00:44:46.790
with an actual
national popular vote,

00:44:46.790 --> 00:44:48.800
or we would quit
faking it and just

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:50.810
let the state
legislature decide,

00:44:50.810 --> 00:44:54.710
and we would have more of
a parliamentary system.

00:44:54.710 --> 00:44:59.840
And we have this one
national vote that

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:01.940
can get thrown out sometimes?

00:45:01.940 --> 00:45:03.200
What's up with that?

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:08.420
So I think we should either
have real hierarchical systems

00:45:08.420 --> 00:45:10.130
or real direct systems.

00:45:10.130 --> 00:45:12.551
And there's a place for each.

00:45:12.551 --> 00:45:14.220
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:16.130
AUDIENCE: On your
redistricting algorithm,

00:45:16.130 --> 00:45:17.780
you talked a lot
about compactness

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:20.420
was there anything about
trying to keep the districts

00:45:20.420 --> 00:45:22.174
of near-equal population?

00:45:22.174 --> 00:45:23.090
BRIAN OLSON: Oh, yeah.

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:25.080
They are all with
equal population

00:45:25.080 --> 00:45:27.560
to within half a percent.

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:31.730
Current maps sometimes
get it down to exactly 1%,

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:34.450
and they're doing funny
business to achieve that.

00:45:34.450 --> 00:45:36.920
So I didn't bother keeping
myself to that strategy.

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:40.490
So I'm just keeping it
to within half a percent

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:43.710
variance between districts.

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:46.130
The traditional
requirements of districts

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:52.060
are equal population and
contiguous, and that's it.

00:45:52.060 --> 00:45:55.790
And at various court
decisions, they

00:45:55.790 --> 00:45:59.540
refused to put any other
restrictions on it,

00:45:59.540 --> 00:46:01.250
and therefore the
state legislature

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:04.772
does whatever partisan
hackery they want.

00:46:04.772 --> 00:46:05.930
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:05.930 --> 00:46:09.800
There's recently some news
coverage about research

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:12.004
into a partisan efficiency gap.

00:46:12.004 --> 00:46:13.670
Have you been following
that, and do you

00:46:13.670 --> 00:46:18.700
have hope that that might
help swing districts away

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:19.640
from gerrymandering?

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:21.020
BRIAN OLSON: Yeah.

00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:24.230
This came up again about
the recent Wisconsin case.

00:46:24.230 --> 00:46:29.150
And it is following that
line of logic I believe

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:33.200
leads to shoddy proportionality
through districting where

00:46:33.200 --> 00:46:36.050
we say, we will make
the districts such

00:46:36.050 --> 00:46:41.660
that this 60-40 state turns out
with 60-40 end representatives,

00:46:41.660 --> 00:46:43.730
which in some ways
would be an improvement

00:46:43.730 --> 00:46:50.660
over the current system where
you have a 48-52% state that

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:54.920
winds up being a 60-40
representation because

00:46:54.920 --> 00:47:00.260
of gerrymandering, really
pushing it that extra gap.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:07.260
So in the balance of
power way, it's better.

00:47:07.260 --> 00:47:09.840
But in terms of actually
representing people,

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:10.520
I'm not sure.

00:47:14.747 --> 00:47:17.080
AUDIENCE: This is a little
bit of an out-there question,

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:23.400
but have you looked at using
your redistricting algorithm,

00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:26.070
or a redistricting
algorithm, for things

00:47:26.070 --> 00:47:27.480
other than districts?

00:47:27.480 --> 00:47:33.510
Like the states, or the
Balkans, or other places

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:36.759
that have somewhat
arbitrary lines.

00:47:36.759 --> 00:47:37.800
What does that look like?

00:47:41.230 --> 00:47:44.070
BRIAN OLSON: It's
on my to-do list of,

00:47:44.070 --> 00:47:46.590
well, what if we
redistricted the Senate?

00:47:46.590 --> 00:47:49.500
Because the US
Senate is nonsensical

00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:52.620
in its current implementation.

00:47:52.620 --> 00:47:57.840
I believe it made
sense in 1790, when

00:47:57.840 --> 00:48:01.440
the states had an
option of being actually

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:05.250
independent mini-nationalities.

00:48:05.250 --> 00:48:08.220
We could have Rhode Island
hanging out with Luxembourg,

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:11.560
and they'd be on equal footing.

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:15.085
But I don't think it
makes sense anymore.

00:48:15.085 --> 00:48:17.910
I would love to see
the US Senate replaced

00:48:17.910 --> 00:48:20.250
with an at-large
proportional body

00:48:20.250 --> 00:48:24.610
with 33 people elected
every two years.

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:26.310
That would be
really interesting,

00:48:26.310 --> 00:48:28.110
to have a national
Senate election.

00:48:30.740 --> 00:48:32.970
But we should probably
try it on a state level

00:48:32.970 --> 00:48:37.440
first, because the states are
the laboratories of democracy.

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:39.490
AUDIENCE: Thanks

00:48:39.490 --> 00:48:42.100
AUDIENCE: In your packing
and cracking slides,

00:48:42.100 --> 00:48:46.000
you showed how to
push a 60/40 populace

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:47.520
to one end or the other.

00:48:47.520 --> 00:48:52.370
Do you have measurements on
how your system approximates

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:57.310
representational voting in all
the states and other algorithms

00:48:57.310 --> 00:48:58.045
as well?

00:48:58.045 --> 00:48:59.710
BRIAN OLSON: That
goes back to, I

00:48:59.710 --> 00:49:02.740
would need to get the partisan
election data in order

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:04.580
to do that kind of modeling.

00:49:04.580 --> 00:49:12.290
So I have the census's
built-in racial demographics

00:49:12.290 --> 00:49:13.700
for my districts.

00:49:13.700 --> 00:49:17.650
So I can tell you, yes, I make
two majority black districts

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:18.640
in Georgia.

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:22.930
But as for party breakdown,
I don't have that data.

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:24.460
AUDIENCE: So
another ramification

00:49:24.460 --> 00:49:27.910
of gerrymandering-- by
creating safe seats, you end up

00:49:27.910 --> 00:49:31.780
getting more radical or
extreme people elected

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:35.140
than reflects the population
as a whole, as we've seen.

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:38.980
So while getting closer
to proportionality

00:49:38.980 --> 00:49:43.289
through districting may seem
unsatisfactory at some level,

00:49:43.289 --> 00:49:45.580
it would also have the effect
of a different population

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:48.590
of elected representatives,
a much more representative

00:49:48.590 --> 00:49:49.900
and a moderate one.

00:49:49.900 --> 00:49:52.240
So that seems like a
highly desirable outcome.

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:56.470
I think coupled with probably
the most pragmatic solution

00:49:56.470 --> 00:50:00.340
to these gerrymandering problems
is the judicial solution,

00:50:00.340 --> 00:50:03.730
and the fact that big data
does allow us to actually

00:50:03.730 --> 00:50:06.745
score these gerrymandering
districts now,

00:50:06.745 --> 00:50:11.500
and to impose requirements that
districting schemes do obey

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:18.310
some computational fairness,
which not only gets us closer--

00:50:18.310 --> 00:50:21.040
yes, less perfectly
satisfactory, but closer

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:26.554
to representational, and
therefore more elected

00:50:26.554 --> 00:50:27.220
representatives.

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:30.469
That seems like a
double goodness.

00:50:30.469 --> 00:50:31.510
How does that strike you?

00:50:36.622 --> 00:50:37.690
BRIAN OLSON: Yeah.

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:39.670
We definitely have a
problem with safe seats.

00:50:42.320 --> 00:50:44.650
I worked a campaign when
I lived in California.

00:50:44.650 --> 00:50:47.890
I was briefly the
volunteer webmaster

00:50:47.890 --> 00:50:52.330
for a congressional
campaign for a few months.

00:50:52.330 --> 00:50:53.380
Let me say that again.

00:50:53.380 --> 00:50:59.080
I was the volunteer webmaster
for a congressional campaign.

00:50:59.080 --> 00:51:03.250
Because they were
running in a district

00:51:03.250 --> 00:51:06.400
that was gerrymandered
against them.

00:51:06.400 --> 00:51:11.320
For many years, California
had a bipartisan gerrymander,

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:15.040
where everybody on both
sides had a safe seat.

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:20.260
And so our party did
not send any help.

00:51:20.260 --> 00:51:22.750
They figured we
were a lost cause.

00:51:22.750 --> 00:51:26.020
And their candidate
would not even

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:28.390
agree to show up
for any debates.

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:32.680
They did not deign to partake
in the democratic process,

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:34.180
because they didn't have to.

00:51:34.180 --> 00:51:36.580
They had a safe seat.

00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:40.390
And there are lots of
sociological analysis

00:51:40.390 --> 00:51:44.830
to be done in saying, oh, all
these safe seat politicians

00:51:44.830 --> 00:51:47.590
are now more extremist,
because some of them

00:51:47.590 --> 00:51:50.530
have had primary challenges
from the extreme wing

00:51:50.530 --> 00:51:51.490
of their party.

00:51:51.490 --> 00:51:54.700
And those are the most motivated
people who actually get out

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:55.570
during a primary.

00:51:55.570 --> 00:52:00.420
So we're representing
2% of the people.

00:52:00.420 --> 00:52:02.877
2% of the people show
up, vote in a primary,

00:52:02.877 --> 00:52:03.710
and that's who wins.

00:52:08.150 --> 00:52:11.570
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
that hierarchical voting

00:52:11.570 --> 00:52:13.955
schemes and direct democracy
each had their place.

00:52:13.955 --> 00:52:15.830
I wondered if you could
say a little bit more

00:52:15.830 --> 00:52:19.870
about which places are more
appropriate for which method.

00:52:22.702 --> 00:52:26.210
BRIAN OLSON: Well, maybe this is
part of the checks and balances

00:52:26.210 --> 00:52:28.010
system of our government.

00:52:28.010 --> 00:52:32.450
We have a state legislature
that is elected from pretty

00:52:32.450 --> 00:52:34.310
small local districts.

00:52:34.310 --> 00:52:38.330
In Massachusetts, some of our
districts are 30,000-something

00:52:38.330 --> 00:52:40.160
people.

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:44.090
And then we also have a governor
who is voted on by everyone.

00:52:44.090 --> 00:52:47.630
So you have that
play right there.

00:52:47.630 --> 00:52:49.370
You have the direct
democracy of,

00:52:49.370 --> 00:52:53.139
everyone votes and gets one
representative for everyone,

00:52:53.139 --> 00:52:55.430
and everyone votes and gets
their local representative,

00:52:55.430 --> 00:52:58.760
who work together in the
milieu of the state House

00:52:58.760 --> 00:52:59.510
to do their thing.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:07.590
And I don't think
we would ever be

00:53:07.590 --> 00:53:12.510
happy with a fully hierarchical
system, because we would then

00:53:12.510 --> 00:53:15.820
lose touch with people
a few levels up,

00:53:15.820 --> 00:53:18.630
and we would see them doing
things, and we would say,

00:53:18.630 --> 00:53:20.642
ah, they don't represent us.

00:53:20.642 --> 00:53:22.725
AUDIENCE: So what you're
saying is you want a mix.

00:53:22.725 --> 00:53:23.560
BRIAN OLSON: Yes.

00:53:23.560 --> 00:53:26.074
AUDIENCE: For these things,
you want this reason.

00:53:26.074 --> 00:53:26.990
You want some of each.

00:53:26.990 --> 00:53:28.080
BRIAN OLSON: Yes.

00:53:28.080 --> 00:53:32.630
[APPLAUSE]

